The problem requires finding the complement of a given integer. We can solve this by converting the integer to binary, flipping all the bits, and then converting it back to decimal.

The algorithm uses a while loop to iterate until the integer becomes 0. In each iteration, it performs a bitwise OR operation between the complement and the integer, and then performs a bitwise XOR operation between the complement and the integer. This flips all the bits in the complement. Finally, it shifts the integer right by one bit.

The time complexity is O(log(n)) because the loop runs log(n) times, where n is the number of bits in the integer. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the complement variable. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs bitwise operations, which are computationally efficient.

